<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09149f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09149f">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09149f"> 149(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Well done, Greenock</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">This name, Luapula, comes from the verb pula, to pierce, and never shall I (or they) forget the great day, twenty years ago, when against the roaring of their war drums, against their tribal order forbidding the intrusive idea, we dared the first ascent (<mark>well done, Greenock!</mark>) of this their sacredly shut river in my Clyde-built schooner, <i>The Messenger of Peace</i>. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 97</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Greenock: town in Scotland and birthplace of Daniel Crawford, as son of a Clyde boat captain. In his first travel account, <cite>Thinking Black</cite> (1912), Crawford writes that the Belgian Commandant in the Congo, was &lsquo;an old Greenock boy, like myself&rsquo; (p.330); and on p.420 it is once again &ldquo;Well done, Greenock!&rdquo;, speaking of the sturdy schooner that carried Crawford up Lake Mweru. </mm> </dd></dl>
